        <!-- Section 1: JC Licklider -->
        <section class="content">
            <h2>1.1 JC Licklider</h2>
            <h3>Who</h3>
            <p><%= lickliderWho || "Joseph Carl Robnett Licklider, commonly known as JC Licklider, was an American psychologist and computer scientist." %></p>

            <h3>What</h3>
            <p><%= lickliderWhat || "Licklider was a pioneer in computer science and conceptualized the 'Intergalactic Computer Network,' which laid the foundation for modern internet ideas." %></p>

            <h3>Why</h3>
            <p><%= lickliderWhy || "He envisioned computers enhancing human communication and collaboration. His ideas eventually shaped the creation of ARPANET, the precursor to the internet." %></p>

            <h3>When</h3>
            <p><%= lickliderWhen || "In the early 1960s, while at ARPA, Licklider’s work significantly influenced networked computing and time-sharing systems." %></p>

            <h3>How</h3>
            <p><%= lickliderHow || "Through his role at ARPA, he supported and funded projects focused on networking, enabling the eventual development of ARPANET." %></p>

            <div class="example">
                <h4>Example:</h4>
                <p>Read Licklider's influential paper, "<a href="<%= lickliderLink || 'https://worrydream.com/refs/Licklider_1960_-_Man-Computer_Symbiosis.pdf' %>" target="_blank">Man-Computer Symbiosis</a>," where he envisions human-computer interaction for collaborative work.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 2: Nuclear Weapons -->
        <section class="content">
            <h2>1.2 Nuclear Weapons</h2>
            <h3>Who</h3>
            <p><%= nuclearWho || "During the Cold War, the U.S. and Soviet Union developed nuclear arsenals, influencing the need for secure communication." %></p>

            <h3>What</h3>
            <p><%= nuclearWhat || "The presence and threat of nuclear weapons led to a push for a resilient, decentralized communication system to withstand nuclear attacks." %></p>

            <h3>Why</h3>
            <p><%= nuclearWhy || "Maintaining communication and command control during nuclear strikes was essential, spurring innovation in network resilience." %></p>

            <h3>When</h3>
            <p><%= nuclearWhen || "In the 1960s, the U.S. Department of Defense prioritized creating systems capable of surviving catastrophic events." %></p>

            <h3>How</h3>
            <p><%= nuclearHow || "This led to the development of ARPANET, which used packet-switching to reroute data through multiple pathways, ensuring communication continuity." %></p>

            <div class="example">
                <h4>Example:</h4>
                <p>Read about the impact of packet-switching technology on modern networks in "<a href="<%= nuclearLink || 'https://www.internetsociety.org/internet/history-internet/brief-history-internet' %>" target="_blank">A Brief History of the Internet</a>" by the Internet Society.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 3: ARPA -->
        <section class="content">
            <h2>1.3 ARPA (Advanced Research Project Agency)</h2>
            <h3>Who</h3>
            <p><%= arpaWho || "ARPA, later known as DARPA, is a U.S. government agency focused on defense-related technological advancements." %></p>

            <h3>What</h3>
            <p><%= arpaWhat || "ARPA was instrumental in creating ARPANET, the first packet-switching network and a precursor to the modern internet." %></p>

            <h3>Why</h3>
            <p><%= arpaWhy || "In response to the Soviet Union’s launch of Sputnik, ARPA was established to drive American innovation in technology and defense." %></p>

            <h3>When</h3>
            <p><%= arpaWhen || "Founded in 1958, ARPA’s involvement in networking technology became prominent in the 1960s with ARPANET's development starting in 1969." %></p>

            <h3>How</h3>
            <p><%= arpaHow || "Through extensive funding in networking research, ARPA connected research institutions, facilitating data sharing and ultimately evolving into the global internet." %></p>

            <div class="example">
                <h4>Example:</h4>
                <p>Learn more about ARPA’s contributions in "<a href="<%= arpaLink || 'https://www.darpa.mil/about-us/timeline/arpanet' %>" target="_blank">ARPANET and the Internet</a>" from the official DARPA timeline.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

